# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: crystal-oscillators-deep
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/colpitts-oscillator] A **Colpitts oscillator**, invented in 1918 by Canadian-American engineer Edwin H.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/colpitts-oscillator] Colpitts using vacuum tubes, is one of a number of designs for LC oscillators, electronic oscillators that use a combination of inductors (L) and capacitors (C) to produce an oscillation at a certain frequency.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/colpitts-oscillator] The distinguishing feature of the Colpitts oscillator is that the feedback for the active device is taken from a voltage divider made of two capacitors in series across the inductor.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/colpitts-oscillator] The amplifier will have differing input and output impedances, and these need to be coupled into the LC circuit without overly damping it.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/colpitts-oscillator] A Colpitts oscillator uses a pair of capacitors to provide voltage division to couple the energy in and out of the tuned circuit.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/colpitts-oscillator] (It can be considered as the electrical dual of a Hartley oscillator, where the feedback signal is taken from an "inductive" voltage divider consisting of two coils in series (or a tapped coil).) Fig.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/colpitts-oscillator] 1 shows the common-base Colpitts circuit.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/colpitts-oscillator] The inductor *L* and the series combination of *C*1 and *C*2 form the resonant tank circuit, which determines the frequency of the oscillator.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/colpitts-oscillator] The voltage across *C*2 is applied to the base-emitter junction of the transistor, as feedback to create oscillations.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/colpitts-oscillator] Here the voltage across *C*1 provides feedback.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/colpitts-oscillator] The actual frequency of oscillation will be slightly lower due to junction capacitances and resistive loading of the transistor.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/colpitts-oscillator] As with any oscillator, the amplification of the active component should be marginally larger than the attenuation of the resonator losses and its voltage division, to obtain stable operation.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/colpitts-oscillator] Thus, a Colpitts oscillator used as a variable-frequency oscillator (VFO) performs best when a variable inductance is used for tuning, as opposed to tuning just one of the two capacitors.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/colpitts-oscillator] If tuning by variable capacitor is needed, it should be done with a third capacitor connected in parallel to the inductor (or in series as in the Clapp oscillator).
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/colpitts-oscillator] 3 shows an example with component values.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/colpitts-oscillator] Instead of field-effect transistors, other active components such as bipolar junction transistors or vacuum tubes, capable of producing gain at the desired frequency, could be used.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/colpitts-oscillator] The common gate amplifier has a low input impedance and a high output impedance.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/colpitts-oscillator] Therefore, the amplifier input, the source, is connected to the low impedance tap of the LC circuit L1, C1, C2, C3 and the amplifier output, the drain, is connected to the high impedance top of the LC circuit.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/colpitts-oscillator] The resistor R1 sets the operating point to 0.5mA drain current with no oscillating.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/colpitts-oscillator] The output is at the low impedance tap and can drive some load.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/colpitts-oscillator] Still, this circuit has low harmonic distortion.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/colpitts-oscillator] An additional variable capacitor between drain of J1 and ground allows to change the frequency of the circuit.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/colpitts-oscillator] The load resistor RL is part of the simulation, not part of the circuit.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/colpitts-oscillator] One method of oscillator analysis is to determine the input impedance of an input port neglecting any reactive components.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/colpitts-oscillator] If the impedance yields a negative resistance term, oscillation is possible.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/colpitts-oscillator] This method will be used here to determine conditions of oscillation and the frequency of oscillation.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/colpitts-oscillator] This configuration models the common collector circuit in the section above.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/colpitts-oscillator] For initial analysis, parasitic elements and device non-linearities will be ignored.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/colpitts-oscillator] These terms can be included later in a more rigorous analysis.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/colpitts-oscillator] Even with these approximations, acceptable comparison with experimental results is possible.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/colpitts-oscillator] where $v_{1}$ is the input voltage, and $i_{1}$ is the input current.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/colpitts-oscillator] where $g_{m}$ is the transconductance of the transistor.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/colpitts-oscillator] If $Z_{1}$ and $Z_{2}$ are complex and of the same sign, then $R_{\text{in}}$ will be a negative resistance.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/colpitts-oscillator] If an inductor is connected to the input, then the circuit will oscillate if the magnitude of the negative resistance is greater than the resistance of the inductor and any stray elements.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/colpitts-oscillator] The frequency of oscillation is as given in the previous section.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/colpitts-oscillator] For the example oscillator above, the emitter current is roughly 1 mA.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/colpitts-oscillator] This value should be sufficient to overcome any positive resistance in the circuit.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/colpitts-oscillator] By inspection, oscillation is more likely for larger values of transconductance and smaller values of capacitance.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/colpitts-oscillator] A more complicated analysis of the common-base oscillator reveals that a low-frequency amplifier voltage gain must be at least 4 to achieve oscillation.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/colpitts-oscillator] If the two capacitors are replaced by inductors, and magnetic coupling is ignored, the circuit becomes a Hartley oscillator.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/colpitts-oscillator] In the Hartley circuit, oscillation is more likely for larger values of transconductance and larger values of inductance.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/colpitts-oscillator] The above analysis also describes the behavior of the Pierce oscillator.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/colpitts-oscillator] The Pierce oscillator, with two capacitors and one inductor, is equivalent to the Colpitts oscillator.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/colpitts-oscillator] Equivalence can be shown by choosing the junction of the two capacitors as the ground point.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/colpitts-oscillator] An electrical dual of the standard Pierce oscillator using two inductors and one capacitor is equivalent to the Hartley oscillator.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/colpitts-oscillator] A Colpitts oscillator is an electronic circuit that generates a sinusoidal waveform, typically in the radio frequency range.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/colpitts-oscillator] It uses an inductor and two capacitors in parallel to form a resonant tank circuit, which determines the oscillation frequency.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/colpitts-oscillator] The output signal from the tank circuit is fed back into the input of an amplifier, where it is amplified and fed back into the tank circuit.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/colpitts-oscillator] The feedback signal provides the necessary phase shift for sustained oscillation.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/colpitts-oscillator] The Colpitts oscillator is widely used in various applications, such as RF communication systems, signal generators, and electronic testing equipment.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/colpitts-oscillator] It has better frequency stability than the Hartley oscillator, which uses a tapped inductor instead of a tapped capacitor in the tank circuit.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/colpitts-oscillator] However, the Colpitts oscillator may require a higher supply voltage and a larger coupling capacitor than the Hartley oscillator.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/colpitts-oscillator] The amplitude of oscillation is generally difficult to predict, but it can often be accurately estimated using the describing function method.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/colpitts-oscillator] where $I_{C}$ is the bias current, and $R_{L}$ is the load resistance at the collector.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/colpitts-oscillator] This assumes that the transistor does not saturate, the collector current flows in narrow pulses, and that the output voltage is sinusoidal (low distortion).
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/colpitts-oscillator] This approximate result also applies to oscillators employing different active device, such as MOSFETs and vacuum tubes.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] A **crystal oscillator** is an electronic oscillator circuit that uses a piezoelectric crystal as a frequency-selective element.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] The oscillator frequency is often used to keep track of time, as in quartz wristwatches, to provide a stable clock signal for digital integrated circuits, and to stabilize frequencies for radio transmitters and receivers.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] The most common type of piezoelectric resonator used is a quartz crystal, so oscillator circuits incorporating them became known as crystal oscillators.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] However, other piezoelectric materials including polycrystalline ceramics are used in similar circuits.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] A crystal oscillator relies on the slight change in shape of a quartz crystal under an electric field, a property known as inverse piezoelectricity.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] A voltage applied to the electrodes on the crystal causes it to change shape; when the voltage is removed, the crystal generates a small voltage as it elastically returns to its original shape.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] The quartz oscillates at a stable resonant frequency (relative to other low-priced oscillators) with frequency accuracy measured in parts per million (ppm).
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] It behaves like an RLC circuit, but with a much higher Q factor (lower energy loss on each cycle of oscillation and higher frequency selectivity) than can be reliably achieved with discrete capacitors (C) and inductors (L), which suffer from parasitic resistance (R).
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Once a quartz crystal is adjusted to a particular frequency (which is affected by the mass of electrodes attached to the crystal, the orientation of the crystal, temperature and other factors), it maintains that frequency with high stability.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Quartz crystals are manufactured for frequencies from a few tens of kilohertz to hundreds of megahertz.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] As of 2003, around two billion crystals were manufactured annually.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Most are used for consumer devices such as wristwatches, clocks, radios, computers, and cellphones.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] However, in applications where small size and weight is needed crystals can be replaced by thin-film bulk acoustic resonators, specifically if ultra-high frequency (more than roughly 1.5 GHz) resonance is needed.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Quartz crystals are also found inside test and measurement equipment, such as counters, signal generators, and oscilloscopes.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] A crystal oscillator is an electric oscillator type circuit that uses a piezoelectric resonator, a crystal, as its frequency-determining element.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] *Crystal* is the common term used in electronics for the frequency-determining component, a wafer of quartz crystal or ceramic with electrodes connected to it.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] A more accurate term for "crystal" is *piezoelectric resonator*.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Crystals are also used in other types of electronic circuits, such as crystal filters.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Piezoelectric resonators are sold as separate components for use in crystal oscillator circuits.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] They are also often incorporated in a single package with the crystal oscillator circuit.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Piezoelectricity was discovered by Jacques and Pierre Curie in 1880.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Paul Langevin first investigated quartz resonators for use in sonar during World War I.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] The first crystal-controlled oscillator, using a crystal of Rochelle salt, was built in 1917 and patented in 1918 by Alexander M.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Nicolson at Western Electric, although his priority was disputed by Walter Guyton Cady.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Cady built the first quartz crystal oscillator in 1921.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Other early innovators in quartz crystal oscillators include G.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Quartz crystal oscillators were developed for high-stability frequency references during the 1920s and 1930s.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Prior to crystals, radio stations controlled their frequency with tuned circuits, which could easily drift off frequency by 3–4 kHz.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Since broadcast stations were assigned frequencies only 10 kHz (Americas) or 9 kHz (elsewhere) apart, interference between adjacent stations due to frequency drift was a common problem.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] In 1925, Westinghouse installed a crystal oscillator in its flagship station KDKA, and by 1926, quartz crystals were used to control the frequency of many broadcasting stations and were popular with amateur radio operators.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] In 1928, Warren Marrison of Bell Laboratories developed the first quartz-crystal clock.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] With accuracies of up to 1 second in 30 years (30 ms/y, or 0.95 ns/s), quartz clocks replaced precision pendulum clocks as the world's most accurate timekeepers until atomic clocks were developed in the 1950s.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Using the early work at Bell Laboratories, American Telephone and Telegraph Company (AT&T) eventually established their Frequency Control Products division, later spun off and known today as Vectron International.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] In 1933, Issac Koga of the Tokyo Institute of Technology reported the R1-cut quartz plate, a temperature-insensitive orientation with a near-zero frequency-temperature coefficient.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Koga-cut crystals were first used in radio transmitters and later in clocks, and the work was recognized as an IEEE Milestone in 2017.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] A number of firms started producing quartz crystals for electronic use during this time.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Using what are now considered primitive methods, about 100,000 crystal units were produced in the United States during 1939.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Through World War II crystals were made from natural quartz crystal, virtually all from Brazil.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] By the 1970s virtually all crystals used in electronics were synthetic.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] In 1968, Juergen Staudte invented a photolithographic process for manufacturing quartz crystal oscillators while working at North American Aviation (now Rockwell) that allowed them to be made small enough for portable products like watches.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Although crystal oscillators still most commonly use quartz crystals, devices using other materials are becoming more common, such as ceramic resonators.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] A crystal is a solid in which the constituent atoms, molecules, or ions are packed in a regularly ordered, repeating pattern extending in all three spatial dimensions.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Almost any object made of an elastic material could be used like a crystal, with appropriate transducers, since all objects have natural resonant frequencies of vibration.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] For example, steel is very elastic and has a high speed of sound.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] It was often used in mechanical filters before quartz.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] The resonant frequency depends on size, shape, elasticity, and the speed of sound in the material.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] High-frequency crystals are typically cut in the shape of a simple rectangle or circular disk.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Low-frequency crystals, such as those used in digital watches, are typically cut in the shape of a tuning fork.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] For applications not needing very precise timing, a low-cost ceramic resonator is often used in place of a quartz crystal.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] When a crystal of quartz is properly cut and mounted, it can be made to distort in an electric field by applying a voltage to an electrode near or on the crystal.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] This property is known as inverse piezoelectricity.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] When the field is removed, the quartz generates an electric field as it returns to its previous shape, and this can generate a voltage.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] The result is that a quartz crystal behaves like an RLC circuit, composed of an inductor, capacitor and resistor, with a precise resonant frequency.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Quartz has the further advantage that its elastic constants and its size change in such a way that the frequency dependence on temperature can be very low.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] The specific characteristics depend on the mode of vibration and the angle at which the quartz is cut (relative to its crystallographic axes).
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Therefore, the resonant frequency of the plate, which depends on its size, does not change much.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] This means that a quartz clock, filter or oscillator remains accurate.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] For critical applications the quartz oscillator is mounted in a temperature-controlled container, called a crystal oven, and can also be mounted on shock absorbers to prevent perturbation by external mechanical vibrations.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] A quartz crystal can be modeled as an electrical network with low-impedance (series) and high-impedance (parallel) resonance points spaced closely together.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] where s is the complex frequency ( $s=j\omega$ ), $\omega _{\mathrm {s} }$ is the series resonant angular frequency, and $\omega _{\mathrm {p} }$ is the parallel resonant angular frequency.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Adding capacitance across a crystal causes the (parallel) resonant frequency to decrease.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Adding inductance across a crystal causes the (parallel) resonant frequency to increase.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] These effects can be used to adjust the frequency at which a crystal oscillates.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Crystal manufacturers normally cut and trim their crystals to have a specified resonant frequency with a known "load" capacitance added to the crystal.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] For example, a crystal intended for a 6 pF load has its specified parallel resonant frequency when a 6.0 pF capacitor is placed across it.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Without the load capacitance, the resonant frequency is higher.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] A quartz crystal provides both series and parallel resonance.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] The series resonance is a few kilohertz lower than the parallel one.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Crystals below 30 MHz are generally operated between series and parallel resonance, which means that the crystal appears as an inductive reactance in operation, this inductance forming a parallel resonant circuit with externally connected parallel capacitance.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Any small additional capacitance in parallel with the crystal pulls the frequency lower.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Moreover, the effective inductive reactance of the crystal can be reduced by adding a capacitor in series with the crystal.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] This latter technique can provide a useful method of trimming the oscillatory frequency within a narrow range; in this case inserting a capacitor in series with the crystal raises the frequency of oscillation.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] For a crystal to operate at its specified frequency, the electronic circuit has to be exactly that specified by the crystal manufacturer.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Note that these points imply a subtlety concerning crystal oscillators in this frequency range: the crystal does not usually oscillate at precisely either of its resonant frequencies.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Crystals above 30 MHz (up to >200 MHz) are generally operated at series resonance where the impedance appears at its minimum and equal to the series resistance.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] For these crystals the series resistance is specified (<100 Ω) instead of the parallel capacitance.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] To reach higher frequencies, a crystal can be made to vibrate at one of its overtone modes, which occur near multiples of the fundamental resonant frequency.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Such a crystal is referred to as a 3rd, 5th, or even 7th overtone crystal.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] To accomplish this, the oscillator circuit usually includes additional LC circuits to select the desired overtone.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] A crystal's frequency characteristic depends on the shape or "cut" of the crystal.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] A tuning-fork crystal is usually cut such that its frequency dependence on temperature is quadratic with the maximum around 25 °C (77 °F).
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] This means that a tuning-fork crystal oscillator resonates close to its target frequency at room temperature, but slows when the temperature either increases or decreases from room temperature.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] The crystal oscillator circuit sustains oscillation by taking a voltage signal from the quartz resonator, amplifying it, and feeding it back to the resonator.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] The rate of expansion and contraction of the quartz is the resonant frequency, and is determined by the cut and size of the crystal.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] When the energy of the generated output frequencies matches the losses in the circuit, an oscillation can be sustained.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] An oscillator crystal has two electrically conductive plates, with a slice or tuning fork of quartz crystal sandwiched between them.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] During startup, the controlling circuit places the crystal into an unstable equilibrium, and due to the positive feedback in the system, any tiny fraction of noise is amplified, ramping up the oscillation.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] The crystal resonator can also be seen as a highly frequency-selective filter in this system: it only passes a very narrow subband of frequencies around the resonant one, attenuating everything else.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Eventually, only the resonant frequency is active.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] As the oscillator amplifies the signals coming out of the crystal, the signals in the crystal's frequency band becomes stronger, eventually dominating the output of the oscillator.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] The narrow resonance band of the quartz crystal filters out the unwanted frequencies.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] The output frequency of a quartz oscillator can be either that of the fundamental resonance or of a multiple of that resonance, called a harmonic frequency.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Harmonics are an exact integer multiple of the fundamental frequency.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] But, like many other mechanical resonators, crystals exhibit several modes of oscillation, usually at approximately odd integer multiples of the fundamental frequency.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] These are termed "overtone modes", and oscillator circuits can be designed to excite them.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] The overtone modes are at frequencies which are approximate, but not exact odd integer multiples of that of the fundamental mode, and overtone frequencies are therefore not exact harmonics of the fundamental.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] High frequency crystals are often designed to operate at third, fifth, or seventh overtones.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Manufacturers have difficulty producing crystals thin enough to produce fundamental frequencies over 30 MHz.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] A fundamental crystal oscillator circuit is simpler and more efficient and has more pullability than a third overtone circuit.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Depending on the manufacturer, the highest available fundamental frequency may be 25 MHz to 66 MHz.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] A major reason for the wide use of crystal oscillators is their high Q factor.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] A typical *Q* value for a quartz oscillator ranges from 104 to 106, compared to perhaps 102 for an LC oscillator.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] The maximum *Q* for a high stability quartz oscillator can be estimated as *Q* = 1.6 × 107/*f*, where *f* is the resonant frequency in megahertz.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] One of the most important traits of quartz crystal oscillators is that they can exhibit very low phase noise.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] In many oscillators, any spectral energy at the resonant frequency is amplified by the oscillator, resulting in a collection of tones at different phases.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] In a crystal oscillator, the crystal mostly vibrates in one axis, therefore only one phase is dominant.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] This property of low phase noise makes them particularly useful in telecommunications where stable signals are needed, and in scientific equipment where very precise time references are needed.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Environmental changes of temperature, humidity, pressure, and vibration can change the resonant frequency of a quartz crystal, but there are several designs that reduce these environmental effects.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] These include the TCXO, MCXO, and OCXO which are defined below.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] These designs, particularly the OCXO, often produce devices with excellent short-term stability.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] The limitations in short-term stability are due mainly to noise from electronic components in the oscillator circuits.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Long-term stability is limited by aging of the crystal.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Due to aging and environmental factors (such as temperature and vibration), it is difficult to keep even the best quartz oscillators within one part in 1010 of their nominal frequency without constant adjustment.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] For this reason, atomic oscillators are used for applications requiring better long-term stability and accuracy.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] For crystals operated at series resonance or pulled away from the main mode by the inclusion of a series inductor or capacitor, significant (and temperature-dependent) spurious responses may be experienced.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Though most spurious modes are typically some tens of kilohertz above the wanted series resonance, their temperature coefficient is different from the main mode, and the spurious response may move through the main mode at certain temperatures.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Even if the series resistances at the spurious resonances appear higher than the one at the wanted frequency, a rapid change in the main mode series resistance can occur at specific temperatures when the two frequencies are coincidental.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] A consequence of these activity dips is that the oscillator may lock at a spurious frequency at specific temperatures.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] This is generally minimized by ensuring that the maintaining circuit has insufficient gain to activate unwanted modes.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Spurious frequencies are also generated by subjecting the crystal to vibration.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] This modulates the resonant frequency to a small degree by the frequency of the vibrations.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] SC-cut (Stress Compensated) crystals are designed to minimize the frequency effect of mounting stress and they are therefore less sensitive to vibration.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Acceleration effects including gravity are also reduced with SC-cut crystals, as is frequency change with time due to long term mounting stress variation.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] There are disadvantages with SC-cut shear mode crystals, such as the need for the maintaining oscillator to discriminate against other closely related unwanted modes and increased frequency change due to temperature when subject to a full ambient range.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] SC-cut crystals are most advantageous where temperature control at their temperature of zero temperature coefficient (turnover) is possible, under these circumstances an overall stability performance from premium units can approach the stability of rubidium frequency standards.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Crystals can be manufactured for oscillation over a wide range of frequencies, from a few kilohertz up to several hundred megahertz.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Many applications call for a crystal oscillator frequency conveniently related to some other desired frequency, so hundreds of standard crystal frequencies are made in large quantities and stocked by electronics distributors.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] For example 3.579545 MHz crystals, which were made in large quantities for NTSC color television receivers, are now popular for many non-television applications (although most modern television receivers now use other frequency crystals for the color decoder).
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Using frequency dividers, frequency multipliers and phase-locked loop circuits, it is practical to derive a wide range of frequencies from one reference frequency.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] The most common material for oscillator crystals is quartz.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] At the beginning of the technology, natural quartz crystals were used but now synthetic crystalline quartz grown by hydrothermal synthesis is predominant due to higher purity, lower cost and more convenient handling.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] One of the few remaining uses of natural crystals is for pressure transducers in deep wells.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] During World War II and for some time afterwards, natural quartz was considered a strategic material by the USA.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Large crystals were imported from Brazil.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Raw "lascas", the source material quartz for hydrothermal synthesis, are imported to USA or mined locally by Coleman Quartz.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] The average value of as-grown synthetic quartz in 1994 was 60 USD/kg.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Two types of quartz crystals exist: left-handed and right-handed.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] The two differ in their optical rotation but they are identical in other physical properties.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Both left and right-handed crystals can be used for oscillators, if the cut angle is correct.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] In manufacture, right-handed quartz is generally used.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] The SiO4 tetrahedrons form parallel helices; the direction of twist of the helix determines the left- or right-hand orientation.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] The helixes are aligned along the c-axis and merged, sharing atoms.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] The mass of the helixes forms a mesh of small and large channels parallel to the c-axis.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] The large ones are large enough to allow some mobility of smaller ions and molecules through the crystal.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] At 573 °C at 1 atmosphere (and at higher temperatures and higher pressures) the α-quartz undergoes quartz inversion, transforms reversibly to β-quartz.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] The reverse process however is not entirely homogeneous and crystal twinning occurs.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Care must be taken during manufacturing and processing to avoid phase transformation.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Other phases, e.g. the higher-temperature phases tridymite and cristobalite, are not significant for oscillators.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] All quartz oscillator crystals are the α-quartz type.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Infrared spectrophotometry is used as one of the methods for measuring the quality of the grown crystals.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] The measured value is based on the absorption bands of the OH radical and the infrared Q value is calculated.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] The electronic grade crystals, grade C, have Q of 1.8 million or above; the premium grade B crystals have Q of 2.2 million, and special premium grade A crystals have Q of 3.0 million.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] The Q value is calculated only for the z region; crystals containing other regions can be adversely affected.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Another quality indicator is the etch channel density; when the crystal is etched, tubular channels are created along linear defects.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] For processing involving etching, e.g. the wristwatch tuning fork crystals, low etch channel density is desirable.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] The etch channel density for swept quartz is about 10–100 and significantly more for unswept quartz.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Presence of etch channels and etch pits degrades the resonator's Q and introduces nonlinearities.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Quartz crystals can be grown for specific purposes.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Crystals for AT-cut are the most common in mass production of oscillator materials; the shape and dimensions are optimized for high yield of the required wafers.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] High-purity quartz crystals are grown with especially low content of aluminium, alkali metal and other impurities and minimal defects; the low amount of alkali metals provides increased resistance to ionizing radiation.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Crystals for wrist watches, for cutting the tuning fork 32768 Hz crystals, are grown with very low etch channel density.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Crystals for SAW devices are grown as flat, with large X-size seed with low etch channel density.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Special high-Q crystals, for use in highly stable oscillators, are grown at constant slow speed and have constant low infrared absorption along the entire Z axis.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Crystals can be grown as Y-bar, with a seed crystal in bar shape and elongated along the Y axis, or as Z-plate, grown from a plate seed with Y-axis direction length and X-axis width.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] The region around the seed crystal contains a large number of crystal defects and should not be used for the wafers.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Crystals grow anisotropically; the growth along the Z axis is up to 3 times faster than along the X axis.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] The growth direction and rate also influences the rate of uptake of impurities.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Y-bar crystals, or Z-plate crystals with long Y axis, have four growth regions usually called +X, −X, Z, and S.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] The distribution of impurities during growth is uneven; different growth areas contain different levels of contaminants.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] The Z regions are the purest, the small occasionally present S regions are less pure, the +X region is yet less pure, and the -X region has the highest level of impurities.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] The impurities have a negative impact on radiation hardness, susceptibility to twinning, filter loss, and long and short term stability of the crystals.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Different-cut seeds in different orientations may provide other kinds of growth regions.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] The growth speed of the −X direction is slowest due to the effect of adsorption of water molecules on the crystal surface; aluminium impurities suppress growth in two other directions.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] The content of aluminium is lowest in Z region, higher in +X, yet higher in −X, and highest in S; the size of S regions also grows with increased amount of aluminium present.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] The content of hydrogen is lowest in Z region, higher in +X region, yet higher in S region, and highest in −X.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Aluminium inclusions transform into color centers with gamma-ray irradiation, causing a darkening of the crystal proportional to the dose and level of impurities; the presence of regions with different darkness reveals the different growth regions.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] The dominant type of defect of concern in quartz crystals is the substitution of an Al(III) for a Si(IV) atom in the crystal lattice.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] The aluminium ion has an associated interstitial charge compensator present nearby, which can be a H+ ion (attached to the nearby oxygen and forming a hydroxyl group, called Al−OH defect), Li+ ion, Na+ ion, K+ ion (less common), or an electron hole trapped in a nearby oxygen atom orbital.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] The composition of the growth solution, whether it is based on lithium or sodium alkali compounds, determines the charge compensating ions for the aluminium defects.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] The ion impurities are of concern as they are not firmly bound and can migrate through the crystal, altering the local lattice elasticity and the resonant frequency of the crystal.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Other common impurities of concern are e.g. iron(III) (interstitial), fluorine, boron(III), phosphorus(V) (substitution), titanium(IV) (substitution, universally present in magmatic quartz, less common in hydrothermal quartz), and germanium(IV) (substitution).
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Sodium and iron ions can cause inclusions of acnite and elemeusite crystals.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Inclusions of water may be present in fast-grown crystals; interstitial water molecules are abundant near the crystal seed.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Another defect of importance is the hydrogen containing growth defect, when instead of a Si−O−Si structure, a pair of Si−OH HO−Si groups is formed; essentially a hydrolyzed bond.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Fast-grown crystals contain more hydrogen defects than slow-grown ones.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] These growth defects source as supply of hydrogen ions for radiation-induced processes and forming Al-OH defects.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Germanium impurities tend to trap electrons created during irradiation; the alkali metal cations then migrate towards the negatively charged center and form a stabilizing complex.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Matrix defects can also be present; oxygen vacancies, silicon vacancies (usually compensated by 4 hydrogens or 3 hydrogens and a hole), peroxy groups, etc.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Some of the defects produce localized levels in the forbidden band, serving as charge traps; Al(III) and B(III) typically serve as hole traps while electron vacancies, titanium, germanium, and phosphorus atoms serve as electron traps.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] The trapped charge carriers can be released by heating; their recombination is the cause of thermoluminescence.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] The mobility of interstitial ions depends strongly on temperature.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Hydrogen ions are mobile down to 10 K, but alkali metal ions become mobile only at temperatures around and above 200 K.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] The hydroxyl defects can be measured by near-infrared spectroscopy.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] The trapped holes can be measured by electron spin resonance.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] The Al−Na+ defects show as an acoustic loss peak due to their stress-induced motion; the Al−Li+ defects do not form a potential well so are not detectable this way.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Some of the radiation-induced defects during their thermal annealing produce thermoluminescence; defects related to aluminium, titanium, and germanium can be distinguished.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Swept crystals are crystals that have undergone a solid-state electrodiffusion purification process.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Sweeping involves heating the crystal above 500 °C in a hydrogen-free atmosphere, with a voltage gradient of at least 1 kV/cm, for several hours (usually over 12).
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] The migration of impurities and the gradual replacement of alkali metal ions with hydrogen (when swept in air) or electron holes (when swept in vacuum) causes a weak electric current through the crystal; decay of this current to a constant value signals the end of the process.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] The crystal is then left to cool, while the electric field is maintained.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] The impurities are concentrated at the cathode region of the crystal, which is cut off afterwards and discarded.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Swept crystals have increased resistance to radiation, as the dose effects are dependent on the level of alkali metal impurities; they are suitable for use in devices exposed to ionizing radiation, e.g. for nuclear and space technology.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Sweeping under vacuum at higher temperatures and higher field strengths yields yet more radiation-hard crystals.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] The level and character of impurities can be measured by infrared spectroscopy.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Quartz can be swept in both α and β phase; sweeping in β phase is faster, but the phase transition may induce twinning.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Twinning can be mitigated by subjecting the crystal to compression stress in the X direction, or an AC or DC electric field along the X axis while the crystal cools through the phase transformation temperature region.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Sweeping can also be used to introduce one kind of an impurity into the crystal.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Lithium, sodium, and hydrogen swept crystals are used for, e.g., studying quartz behavior.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Very small crystals for high fundamental-mode frequencies can be manufactured by photolithography.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Crystals can be adjusted to exact frequencies by laser trimming.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Another method commonly used is electrochemical increase or decrease of silver electrode thickness by submerging a resonator in lapis lazuli dissolved in water, citric acid in water, or water with salt, and using the resonator as one electrode, and a small silver electrode as the other.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] By choosing the direction of current one can either increase or decrease the mass of the electrodes.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Details were published in "Radio" magazine (3/1978) by UB5LEV.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Raising frequency by scratching off parts of the electrodes is not advised as this may damage the crystal and lower its Q factor.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Capacitor trimmers can be also used for frequency adjustment of the oscillator circuit.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Some other piezoelectric materials than quartz can be employed.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Some materials may be more suitable for specific applications.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] An oscillator crystal can be also manufactured by depositing the resonator material on the silicon chip surface.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Crystals of gallium phosphate, langasite, langanite and langatate are about 10 times more pullable than the corresponding quartz crystals, and are used in some VCXO oscillators.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] The frequency stability is determined by the crystal's quality factor (Q factor).
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] It is inversely dependent on the frequency, and on the constant that is dependent on the particular cut.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] The stability of AT cut crystals decreases with increasing frequency.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] For more accurate higher frequencies it is better to use a crystal with lower fundamental frequency, operating at an overtone.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] A badly designed oscillator circuit may suddenly begin oscillating on an overtone.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] In 1972, a train in Fremont, California crashed due to a faulty oscillator.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] An inappropriate value of the tank capacitor caused the crystal in a control board to be overdriven, jumping to an overtone, and causing the train to speed up instead of slowing down.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Temperature influences the operating frequency; various forms of compensation are used, from analog compensation (TCXO) and microcontroller compensation (MCXO) to stabilization of the temperature with a crystal oven (OCXO).
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] The crystals possess temperature hysteresis; the frequency at a given temperature achieved by increasing the temperature is not equal to the frequency on the same temperature achieved by decreasing the temperature.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] The temperature sensitivity depends primarily on the cut; the temperature compensated cuts are chosen as to minimize frequency/temperature dependence.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Special cuts can be made with linear temperature characteristics; the LC cut is used in quartz thermometers.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Other influencing factors are the overtone used, the mounting and electrodes, impurities in the crystal, mechanical strain, crystal geometry, rate of temperature change, thermal history (due to hysteresis), ionizing radiation, and drive level.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Crystals tend to suffer anomalies in their frequency/temperature and resistance/temperature characteristics, known as activity dips.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] These are small downward frequency or upward resistance excursions localized at certain temperatures, with their temperature position dependent on the value of the load capacitors.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Mechanical stresses also influence the frequency.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Other dynamic stress inducing factors are shocks, vibrations, and acoustic noise.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Some cuts are less sensitive to stresses; the SC (stress-compensated) cut is an example.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Atmospheric pressure changes can also introduce deformations to the housing, influencing the frequency by changing stray capacitances.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Atmospheric humidity influences the thermal transfer properties of air, and can change electrical properties of plastics by diffusion of water molecules into their structure, altering the dielectric constants and electrical conductivity.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Other factors influencing the frequency are the power supply voltage, load impedance, magnetic fields, electric fields (in case of cuts that are sensitive to them, e.g., SC cuts), the presence and absorbed dose of γ-particles and ionizing radiation, and the age of the crystal.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Crystals undergo slow gradual change of frequency with time, known as aging.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] The mounting and contacts may undergo relief of the built-in stresses.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Molecules of contamination either from the residual atmosphere, outgassed from the crystal, electrodes or packaging materials, or introduced during sealing the housing can be adsorbed on the crystal surface, changing its mass; this effect is exploited in quartz crystal microbalances.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] The composition of the crystal can be gradually altered by outgassing, diffusion of atoms of impurities or migrating from the electrodes, or the lattice can be damaged by radiation.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Slow chemical reactions may occur on or in the crystal, or on the inner surfaces of the enclosure.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Electrode material, e.g. chromium or aluminium, can react with the crystal, creating layers of metal oxide and silicon; these interface layers can undergo changes in time.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] The pressure in the enclosure can change due to varying atmospheric pressure, temperature, leaks, or outgassing of the materials inside.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Factors outside of the crystal itself are e.g. aging of the oscillator circuitry (and e.g. change of capacitances), and drift of parameters of the crystal oven.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] External atmosphere composition can also influence the aging; hydrogen can diffuse through nickel housing.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Helium can cause similar issues when it diffuses through glass enclosures of rubidium standards.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Gold is a favored electrode material for low-aging resonators; its adhesion to quartz is strong enough to maintain contact even at strong mechanical shocks, but weak enough to not support significant strain gradients (unlike chromium, aluminium, and nickel).
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Gold also does not commonly form oxides; it adsorbs organic contaminants from the air, but these are easy to remove.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] However, gold alone can undergo delamination; a layer of chromium is therefore sometimes used for improved binding strength.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Silver and aluminium are often used as electrodes; however both form oxide layers with time that increases the crystal mass and lowers frequency.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Silver can be passivated by exposure to iodine vapors, forming a layer of silver iodide.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Aluminium oxidizes readily but slowly, until about 5 nm thickness is reached; increased temperature during artificial aging does not significantly increase the oxide forming speed; a thick oxide layer can be formed during manufacture by anodizing.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] A DC voltage bias between the electrodes can accelerate the initial aging, probably by induced diffusion of impurities through the crystal.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Placing a capacitor in series with the crystal and a several-megaohm resistor in parallel can minimize such voltages.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Aging decreases logarithmically with time, the largest changes occurring shortly after manufacture.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Artificially aging a crystal by prolonged storage at 85 to 125 °C can increase its long-term stability.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] High magnitudes of shocks may tear the crystals off their mountings (especially in the case of large low-frequency crystals suspended on thin wires), or cause cracking of the crystal.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Crystals free of surface imperfections are highly shock-resistant; chemical polishing can produce crystals able to survive tens of thousands of g.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Crystals have no inherent failure mechanisms; some have operated in devices for decades.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Failures may be, however, introduced by faults in bonding, leaky enclosures, corrosion, frequency shift by aging, breaking the crystal by too high mechanical shock, or radiation-induced damage when non-swept quartz is used.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Crystals can be also damaged by overdriving.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Crystals suffer from minor short-term frequency fluctuations as well.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] The short-term stability is measured by four main parameters: Allan variance (the most common one specified in oscillator data sheets), phase noise, spectral density of phase deviations, and spectral density of fractional frequency deviations.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] The effects of acceleration and vibration tend to dominate the other noise sources; surface acoustic wave devices tend to be more sensitive than bulk acoustic wave (BAW) ones, and the stress-compensated cuts are even less sensitive.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] The relative orientation of the acceleration vector to the crystal dramatically influences the crystal's vibration sensitivity.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Mechanical vibration isolation mountings can be used for high-stability crystals.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Phase noise plays a significant role in frequency synthesis systems using frequency multiplication; a multiplication of a frequency by N increases the phase noise power by N2.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] A frequency multiplication by 10 times multiplies the magnitude of the phase error by 10 times.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] This can be disastrous for systems employing PLL or FSK technologies.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Magnetic fields have little effect on the crystal itself, as quartz is diamagnetic; eddy currents or AC voltages can however be induced into the circuits, and magnetic parts of the mounting and housing may be influenced.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] After the power-up, the crystals take several seconds to minutes to "warm up" and stabilize their frequency.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] The oven-controlled OCXOs require usually 3–10 minutes for heating up to reach thermal equilibrium; the oven-less oscillators stabilize in several seconds as the few milliwatts dissipated in the crystal cause a small but noticeable level of internal heating.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] The crystals have to be driven at the appropriate drive level.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Low-frequency crystals, especially flexural-mode ones, may fracture at too high drive levels.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] The drive level is specified as the amount of power dissipated in the crystal.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] The appropriate drive levels are about 5 μW for flexural modes up to 100 kHz, 1 μW for fundamental modes at 1–4 MHz, 0.5 μW for fundamental modes 4–20 MHz and 0.5 μW for overtone modes at 20–200 MHz.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Too low drive level may cause problems with starting the oscillator.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Low drive levels are better for higher stability and lower power consumption of the oscillator.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p01] Higher drive levels, in turn, reduce the impact of noise by increasing the signal-to-noise ratio.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p02] The resonator plate can be cut from the source crystal in many different ways.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p02] The orientation of the cut influences the crystal's aging characteristics, frequency stability, thermal characteristics, and other parameters.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p02] These cuts operate at bulk acoustic wave (BAW); for higher frequencies, surface acoustic wave (SAW) devices are employed.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p02] The letter ‘T’ in the cut name marks a temperature-compensated cut – a cut oriented in a way that the temperature coefficients of the lattice are minimal; the FC and SC cuts are also temperature-compensated.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p02] Strip resonators, usually AT cuts, are smaller and therefore less sensitive to mechanical shocks.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p02] At the same frequency and overtone, the strip has less pullability, higher resistance, and higher temperature coefficient.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p02] The low frequency cuts are mounted at the nodes where they are virtually motionless; thin wires are attached at such points on each side between the crystal and the leads.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p02] The large mass of the crystal suspended on the thin wires makes the assembly sensitive to mechanical shocks and vibrations.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p02] The crystals are usually mounted in hermetically sealed glass or metal cases, filled with a dry and inert atmosphere, usually vacuum, nitrogen, or helium.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p02] Plastic housings can be used as well, but those are not hermetic and another secondary sealing has to be built around the crystal.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p02] Several resonator configurations are possible, in addition to the classical way of directly attaching leads to the crystal.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p02] The gap between the electrodes and the resonator act as two small series capacitors, making the crystal less sensitive to circuit influences.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p02] The architecture eliminates the effects of the surface contacts between the electrodes, the constraints in the mounting connections, and the issues related to ion migration from the electrodes into the lattice of the vibrating element.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p02] The resulting configuration is rugged, resistant to shock and vibration, resistant to acceleration and ionizing radiation, and has improved aging characteristics.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p02] AT cut is usually used, though SC cut variants exist as well.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p02] BVA resonators are often used in spacecraft applications.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p02] In the 1930s to 1950s, it was fairly common for people to adjust the frequency of the crystals by manual grinding.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p02] The crystals were ground using a fine abrasive slurry, or even a toothpaste, to increase their frequency.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p02] A slight decrease by 1–2 kHz when the crystal was overground was possible by marking the crystal face with a pencil lead, at the cost of a lowered Q.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p02] The frequency of the crystal is slightly adjustable ("pullable") by modifying the attached capacitances.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p02] A varactor, a diode with capacitance depending on applied voltage, is often used in voltage-controlled crystal oscillators, VCXO.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p02] The crystal cuts are usually AT or rarely SC, and operate in fundamental mode; the amount of available frequency deviation is inversely proportional to the square of the overtone number, so a third overtone has only one-ninth of the pullability of the fundamental mode.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p02] SC cuts, while more stable, are significantly less pullable.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p02] On electrical schematic diagrams, *crystals* are designated with the class letter *Y* (Y1, Y2, etc.).
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p02] Oscillators, whether they are crystal oscillators or others, are designated with the class letter *G* (G1, G2, etc.).
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oscillator-p02] Crystals may also be designated on a schematic with *X* or *XTAL* (a phonetic abbreviation, comparable to using *Xmas* for *Christmas*), or a crystal oscillator with ***XO***.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oven] A **crystal oven** is a temperature-controlled chamber used to maintain the quartz crystal in electronic crystal oscillators at a constant temperature, in order to prevent changes in the frequency due to variations in ambient temperature.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oven] An oscillator of this type is known as an *oven-controlled crystal oscillator* (**OCXO**, where "XO" is an old abbreviation for "crystal oscillator").
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oven] This type of oscillator achieves the highest frequency stability possible with a crystal.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oven] They are typically used to control the frequency of radio transmitters, cellular base stations, military communications equipment, and for precision frequency measurement.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oven] Quartz crystals are widely used in electronic oscillators to precisely control the frequency produced.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oven] The frequency at which a quartz crystal resonator vibrates depends on its physical dimensions.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oven] A change in temperature causes the quartz to expand or contract due to thermal expansion, changing the frequency of the signal produced by the oscillator.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oven] Although quartz has a very low coefficient of thermal expansion, temperature changes are still the major cause of frequency variation in crystal oscillators.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oven] The oven is a thermally insulated enclosure containing the crystal and one or more electrical heating elements.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oven] Since other electronic components in the circuit are also vulnerable to temperature drift, usually the entire oscillator circuit is enclosed in the oven.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oven] A thermistor temperature sensor in a closed-loop control circuit is used to control the power to the heater and ensure that the oven is maintained at the precise temperature desired.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oven] Because the oven operates above ambient temperature, the oscillator usually requires a warm-up period after power has been applied to reach its operating temperature.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oven] During this warm-up period, the frequency will not have the full rated stability.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oven] The temperature selected for the oven is that at which the slope of the crystal's frequency vs. temperature curve is zero, further improving stability.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oven] AT- or SC-cut (stress-compensated) crystals are used.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oven] The SC-cut has a wider temperature range over which near-zero temperature coefficient is achieved and thus reduces warmup time.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oven] Power transistors are usually used for the heaters instead of resistance heating elements.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oven] Their power output is proportional to the current, rather than the square of the current, which linearizes the gain of the control loop.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oven] A common temperature for a crystal oven is 75 °C, but the temperature may vary between 30 and 80 °C depending on setup.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oven] Most standard commercial crystals are specified to an environmental temperature of 0–70 °C, industrial versions are usually specified to −40 to +85 °C.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oven] Because of the power required to run the heater, OCXOs require more power than oscillators that run at ambient temperature, and the requirement for the heater, thermal mass, and thermal insulation means that they are physically larger.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oven] Therefore, they are not used in battery-powered or miniature applications, such as watches.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oven] However, in return, the oven-controlled oscillator achieves the best frequency stability possible from a crystal.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oven] The short-term frequency stability of OCXOs is typically 1×10−12 over a few seconds, while the long-term stability is limited to around 1×10−8 (10 ppb) per year by aging of the crystal.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oven] Achieving better stability requires switching to an atomic frequency standard, such as a rubidium standard, caesium standard, or hydrogen maser.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oven] Another cheaper alternative is to discipline a crystal oscillator with a GPS time signal, creating a GPS-disciplined oscillator (GPSDO).
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oven] Using a GPS receiver that can generate stable time signals (down to within ~30 ns of UTC), a GPSDO can maintain oscillation stability of 10−13 for extended periods of time.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oven] In crystals used for nonlinear optics, phase matching is also sensitive to temperature, and thus they require temperature stabilization, especially as the laser beam heats up the crystal.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oven] Additionally fast retuning of the crystal is often employed.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oven] For this application, the crystal and the thermistor need to be in very close contact and both must have as low a heat capacity as possible.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/crystal-oven] To avoid breaking the crystal, large temperature variations in short times must be avoided.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] An **electronic oscillator** is an electronic circuit that produces a periodic, oscillating or alternating current (AC) signal, usually a sine wave, square wave or a triangle wave, powered by a direct current (DC) source.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] Oscillators are found in many electronic devices, such as radio receivers, television sets, radio and television broadcast transmitters, computers, computer peripherals, cellphones, radar, and many other devices.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] There are two general types of electronic oscillators: the **linear** or **harmonic oscillator**, and the **nonlinear** or **relaxation oscillator**.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] The two types are fundamentally different in how oscillation is produced, as well as in the characteristic type of output signal that is generated.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] The most-common linear oscillator in use is the crystal oscillator, in which the output frequency is controlled by a piezo-electric resonator consisting of a vibrating quartz crystal.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] Crystal oscillators are ubiquitous in modern electronics, being the source for the clock signal in computers and digital watches, as well as a source for the signals generated in radio transmitters and receivers.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] As a crystal oscillator's “native” output waveform is sinusoidal, a signal-conditioning circuit may be used to convert the output to other waveform types, such as the square wave typically utilized in computer clock circuits.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] The most common form of linear oscillator is an electronic amplifier such as a transistor or operational amplifier connected in a feedback loop with its output fed back into its input through a frequency selective electronic filter to provide positive feedback.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] When the power supply to the amplifier is switched on initially, electronic noise in the circuit provides a non-zero signal to get oscillations started.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] The noise travels around the loop and is amplified and filtered until very quickly it converges on a sine wave at a single frequency.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] Typical block diagram of a negative resistance oscillator.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] In some types the negative resistance device is connected in parallel with the resonant circuit.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] Negative-resistance oscillators are usually used at high frequencies in the microwave range and above, since at these frequencies feedback oscillators perform poorly due to excessive phase shift in the feedback path.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] In negative-resistance oscillators, a resonant circuit, such as an LC circuit, crystal, or cavity resonator, is connected across a device with negative differential resistance, and a DC bias voltage is applied to supply energy.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] A resonant circuit by itself is "almost" an oscillator; it can store energy in the form of electronic oscillations if excited, but because it has electrical resistance and other losses the oscillations are damped and decay to zero.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] The negative resistance of the active device cancels the (positive) internal loss resistance in the resonator, in effect creating a resonator circuit with no damping, which generates spontaneous continuous oscillations at its resonant frequency.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] The negative-resistance oscillator model is not limited to one-port devices like diodes; feedback oscillator circuits with two-port amplifying devices such as transistors and tubes also have negative resistance.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] At high frequencies, three terminal devices such as transistors and FETs are also used in negative resistance oscillators.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] At high frequencies these devices do not need a feedback loop, but with certain loads applied to one port can become unstable at the other port and show negative resistance due to internal feedback.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] The negative resistance port is connected to a tuned circuit or resonant cavity, causing them to oscillate.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] High-frequency oscillators in general are designed using negative-resistance techniques.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] A **nonlinear** or **relaxation oscillator** produces a non-sinusoidal output, such as a square, sawtooth or triangle wave.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] It consists of an energy-storing element (a capacitor or, more rarely, an inductor) and a nonlinear switching device (a latch, Schmitt trigger, or negative resistance element) connected in a feedback loop.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] The switching device periodically charges the storage element with energy and when its voltage or current reaches a threshold discharges it again, thus causing abrupt changes in the output waveform.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] Although in the past negative resistance devices like the unijunction transistor, thyratron tube or neon lamp were used, today relaxation oscillators are mainly built with integrated circuits like the 555 timer IC.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] Square-wave relaxation oscillators are used to provide the clock signal for sequential logic circuits such as timers and counters, although crystal oscillators are often preferred for their greater stability.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] Triangle-wave or sawtooth oscillators are used in the timebase circuits that generate the horizontal deflection signals for cathode-ray tubes in analogue oscilloscopes and television sets.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] They are also used in voltage-controlled oscillators (VCOs), inverters and switching power supplies, dual-slope analog to digital converters (ADCs), and in function generators to generate square and triangle waves for testing equipment.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] In general, relaxation oscillators are used at lower frequencies and have poorer frequency stability than linear oscillators.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] Ring oscillators are built of a ring of active delay stages, such as inverters.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] Generally the ring has an odd number of inverting stages, so that there is no single stable state for the internal ring voltages.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] Instead, a single transition propagates endlessly around the ring.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] An oscillator can be designed so that the oscillation frequency can be varied over some range by an input voltage or current.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] These voltage-controlled oscillators are widely used in phase-locked loops, in which the oscillator's frequency can be locked to the frequency of another oscillator.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] These are ubiquitous in modern communications circuits, used in filters, modulators, demodulators, and forming the basis of frequency synthesizer circuits which are used to tune radios and televisions.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] Radio frequency VCOs are usually made by adding a varactor diode to the tuned circuit or resonator in an oscillator circuit.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] Changing the DC voltage across the varactor changes its capacitance, which changes the resonant frequency of the tuned circuit.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] Voltage-controlled relaxation oscillators can be constructed by charging and discharging the energy storage capacitor with a voltage-controlled current source.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] Increasing the input voltage increases the rate of charging the capacitor, decreasing the time between switching events.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] A feedback oscillator circuit consists of two parts connected in a feedback loop; an amplifier A and an electronic filter $\beta (j\omega )$ .
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] The filter's purpose is to limit the frequencies that can pass through the loop so the circuit only oscillates at the desired frequency.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] Since the filter and wires in the circuit have resistance they consume energy and the amplitude of the signal drops as it passes through the filter.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] The amplifier is needed to increase the amplitude of the signal to compensate for the energy lost in the other parts of the circuit, so the loop will oscillate, as well as supply energy to the load attached to the output.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] The ratio of output to input of the loop, ${v_{o} \over v_{i}}=A\beta (j\omega )$ , is called the loop gain.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] If the loop gain were less than one, the signal would decrease around the loop, resulting in an exponentially decaying sine wave that decreases to zero.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] Equations (1) and (2) are called the *Barkhausen stability criterion*.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] It is a necessary but not a sufficient criterion for oscillation, so there are some circuits which satisfy these equations that will not oscillate.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] An equivalent condition often used instead of the Barkhausen condition is that the circuit's closed loop transfer function (the circuit's complex impedance at its output) have a pair of poles on the imaginary axis.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] In general, the phase shift of the feedback network increases with increasing frequency so there are only a few discrete frequencies (often only one) which satisfy the second equation.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] If the amplifier gain A is high enough that the loop gain is unity (or greater, see Startup section) at one of these frequencies, the circuit will oscillate at that frequency.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] Many amplifiers such as common-emitter transistor circuits are "inverting", meaning that their output voltage decreases when their input increases.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] In these the amplifier provides 180° phase shift, so the circuit will oscillate at the frequency at which the feedback network provides the other 180° phase shift.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] An alternate mathematical stability test sometimes used instead of the Barkhausen criterion is the Nyquist stability criterion.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] This has a wider applicability than the Barkhausen, so it can identify some of the circuits which pass the Barkhausen criterion but do not oscillate.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] Temperature changes, other environmental changes, aging, and manufacturing tolerances will cause component values to "drift" away from their designed values.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] Changes in *frequency determining* components such as the tank circuit in LC oscillators will cause the oscillation frequency to change, so for a constant frequency these components must have stable values.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] How stable the oscillator's frequency is to other changes in the circuit, such as changes in values of other components, gain of the amplifier, the load impedance, or the supply voltage, is mainly dependent on the Q factor ("quality factor") of the feedback filter.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] Since the *amplitude* of the output is constant due to the nonlinearity of the amplifier (see Startup section below), changes in component values cause changes in the phase shift $\phi \;=\;\angle A\beta (j\omega )$ of the feedback loop.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] Since oscillation can only occur at frequencies where the phase shift is a multiple of 360°, $\phi \;=\;360n^{\circ }$ , shifts in component values cause the oscillation frequency $\omega _{0}$ to change to bring the loop phase back to 360n°.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] RC oscillators have the equivalent of a very low Q , so the phase changes very slowly with frequency, therefore a given phase change will cause a large change in the frequency.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] In contrast, LC oscillators have tank circuits with high Q (~102).
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] This means the phase shift of the feedback network increases rapidly with frequency near the resonant frequency of the tank circuit.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] So a large change in phase causes only a small change in frequency.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] Therefore, the circuit's oscillation frequency is very close to the natural resonant frequency of the tuned circuit, and doesn't depend much on other components in the circuit.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] The quartz crystal resonators used in crystal oscillators have even higher Q (104 to 106) and their frequency is very stable and independent of other circuit components.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] The frequency of RC and LC oscillators can be tuned over a wide range by using variable components in the filter.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] A microwave cavity can be tuned mechanically by moving one of the walls.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] In contrast, a quartz crystal is a mechanical resonator whose resonant frequency is mainly determined by its dimensions, so a crystal oscillator's frequency is only adjustable over a very narrow range, a tiny fraction of one percent.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] Its frequency can be changed slightly by using a trimmer capacitor in series or parallel with the crystal.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] (1) and (2), merely gives the frequencies at which steady-state oscillation is possible, but says nothing about the amplitude of the oscillation, whether the amplitude is stable, or whether the circuit will start oscillating when the power is turned on.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] A typical rule of thumb is to make the small signal loop gain at the oscillation frequency 2 or 3.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] When the power is turned on, oscillation is started by the power turn-on transient or random electronic noise present in the circuit.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] Noise guarantees that the circuit will not remain "balanced" precisely at its unstable DC equilibrium point (Q point) indefinitely.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] Due to the narrow passband of the filter, the response of the circuit to a noise pulse will be sinusoidal, it will excite a small sine wave of voltage in the loop.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] Since for small signals the loop gain is greater than one, the amplitude of the sine wave increases exponentially.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] During startup, while the amplitude of the oscillation is small, the circuit is approximately linear, so the analysis used in the Barkhausen criterion is applicable.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] When the amplitude becomes large enough that the amplifier becomes nonlinear, generating harmonic distortion, technically the frequency domain analysis used in normal amplifier circuits is no longer applicable, so the "gain" of the circuit is undefined.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] However the filter attenuates the harmonic components produced by the nonlinearity of the amplifier, so the fundamental frequency component $\sin \omega _{0}t$ mainly determines the loop gain (this is the "harmonic balance" analysis technique for nonlinear circuits).
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] The sine wave cannot grow indefinitely; in all real oscillators some nonlinear process in the circuit limits its amplitude, reducing the gain as the amplitude increases, resulting in stable operation at some constant amplitude.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] In most oscillators this nonlinearity is simply the saturation (limiting or clipping) of the amplifying device, the transistor, vacuum tube or op-amp.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] The maximum voltage swing of the amplifier's output is limited by the DC voltage provided by its power supply.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] Another possibility is that the output may be limited by the amplifier slew rate.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] As the amplitude of the output nears the power supply voltage rails, the amplifier begins to saturate on the peaks (top and bottom) of the sine wave, flattening or "clipping" the peaks.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] To achieve the maximum amplitude sine wave output from the circuit, the amplifier should be biased midway between its clipping levels.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] For example, an op amp should be biased midway between the two supply voltage rails.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] A common-emitter transistor amplifier's collector voltage should be biased midway between cutoff and saturation levels.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] Since the output of the amplifier can no longer increase with increasing input, further increases in amplitude cause the equivalent gain of the amplifier and thus the loop gain to decrease.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] This is a stable equilibrium; if the amplitude of the sine wave increases for some reason, increased clipping of the output causes the loop gain $|A\beta (j\omega _{0})|$ to drop below one temporarily, reducing the sine wave's amplitude back to its unity-gain value.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] Similarly if the amplitude of the wave decreases, the decreased clipping will cause the loop gain to increase above one, increasing the amplitude.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] An exception to the above are high Q oscillator circuits such as crystal oscillators; the narrow bandwidth of the crystal removes the harmonics from the output, producing a 'pure' sinusoidal wave with almost no distortion even with large loop gains.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] Since oscillators depend on nonlinearity for their operation, the usual linear frequency domain circuit analysis techniques used for amplifiers based on the Laplace transform, such as root locus and gain and phase plots (Bode plots), cannot capture their full behavior.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] To determine startup and transient behavior and calculate the detailed shape of the output waveform, electronic circuit simulation computer programs like SPICE are used.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] Component values are tweaked until the simulation results are satisfactory.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] The distorted oscillations of real-world (nonlinear) oscillators are called limit cycles and are studied in nonlinear control theory.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] In applications where a 'pure' very low distortion sine wave is needed, such as precision signal generators, a nonlinear component is often used in the feedback loop that provides a 'slow' gain reduction with amplitude.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] This stabilizes the loop gain at an amplitude below the saturation level of the amplifier, so it does not saturate and "clip" the sine wave.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] Resistor-diode networks and FETs are often used for the nonlinear element.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] An older design uses a thermistor or an ordinary incandescent light bulb; both provide a resistance that increases with temperature as the current through them increases.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] As the amplitude of the signal current through them increases during oscillator startup, the increasing resistance of these devices reduces the loop gain.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] The essential characteristic of all these circuits is that the nonlinear gain-control circuit must have a long time constant, much longer than a single period of the oscillation.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] Therefore, over a single cycle they act as virtually linear elements, and so introduce very little distortion.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] The operation of these circuits is somewhat analogous to an automatic gain control (AGC) circuit in a radio receiver.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] The Wien bridge oscillator is a widely used circuit in which this type of gain stabilization is used.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] At high frequencies it becomes difficult to physically implement feedback oscillators because of shortcomings of the components.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] Since at high frequencies the tank circuit has very small capacitance and inductance, parasitic capacitance and parasitic inductance of component leads and PCB traces become significant.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] These may create unwanted feedback paths between the output and input of the active device, creating instability and oscillations at unwanted frequencies (parasitic oscillation).
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] Parasitic feedback paths inside the active device itself, such as the interelectrode capacitance between output and input, make the device unstable.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] The input impedance of the active device falls with frequency, so it may load the feedback network.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] As a result, stable feedback oscillators are difficult to build for frequencies above 500 MHz, and negative resistance oscillators are usually used for frequencies above this.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] The first practical oscillators were based on electric arcs, which were used for lighting in the 19th century.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] Ernst Lecher in 1888 showed that the current through an electric arc could be oscillatory.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] An oscillator was built by Elihu Thomson in 1892 by placing an LC tuned circuit in parallel with an electric arc and included a magnetic blowout.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] The arc oscillator was rediscovered and popularized by William Duddell in 1900.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] Duddell, a student at London Technical College, was investigating the hissing arc effect.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] He attached an LC circuit (tuned circuit) to the electrodes of an arc lamp, and the negative resistance of the arc excited oscillation in the tuned circuit.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] Some of the energy was radiated as sound waves by the arc, producing a musical tone.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] Duddell demonstrated his oscillator before the London Institute of Electrical Engineers by sequentially connecting different tuned circuits across the arc to play the national anthem "God Save the Queen".
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] Duddell's "singing arc" did not generate frequencies above the audio range.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] In 1902 Danish physicists Valdemar Poulsen and P.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] Pederson were able to increase the frequency produced into the radio range by operating the arc in a hydrogen atmosphere with a magnetic field, inventing the Poulsen arc radio transmitter, the first continuous wave radio transmitter, which was used through the 1920s.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] The vacuum-tube feedback oscillator was invented around 1912, when it was discovered that feedback ("regeneration") in the recently invented audion (triode) vacuum tube could produce oscillations.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] At least six researchers independently made this discovery, although not all of them can be said to have a role in the invention of the oscillator.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] In the summer of 1912, Edwin Armstrong observed oscillations in audion radio receiver circuits and went on to use positive feedback in his invention of the regenerative receiver.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] Austrian Alexander Meissner independently discovered positive feedback and invented oscillators in March 1913.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] Irving Langmuir at General Electric observed feedback in 1913.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] Fritz Lowenstein may have preceded the others with a crude oscillator in late 1911.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] Round patented amplifying and oscillating circuits in 1913.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] In August 1912, Lee De Forest, the inventor of the audion, had also observed oscillations in his amplifiers, but he didn't understand the significance and tried to eliminate it until he read Armstrong's patents in 1914, which he promptly challenged.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] Armstrong and De Forest fought a protracted legal battle over the rights to the "regenerative" oscillator circuit which has been called "the most complicated patent litigation in the history of radio".
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] De Forest ultimately won before the Supreme Court in 1934 on technical grounds, but most sources regard Armstrong's claim as the stronger one.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] The first and most widely used relaxation oscillator circuit, the astable multivibrator, was invented in 1917 by French engineers Henri Abraham and Eugene Bloch.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] They called their cross-coupled, dual-vacuum-tube circuit a *multivibrateur*, because the square-wave signal it produced was rich in harmonics, compared to the sinusoidal signal of other vacuum-tube oscillators.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] Vacuum-tube feedback oscillators became the basis of radio transmission by 1920.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] However, the triode vacuum tube oscillator performed poorly above 300 MHz because of interelectrode capacitance.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] To reach higher frequencies, new "transit time" (velocity modulation) vacuum tubes were developed, in which electrons traveled in "bunches" through the tube.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] The first of these was the Barkhausen–Kurz oscillator (1920), the first tube to produce power in the UHF range.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] The most important and widely used were the klystron (R. and S.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] Varian, 1937) and the cavity magnetron (J.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] Mathematical conditions for feedback oscillations, now called the Barkhausen criterion, were derived by Heinrich Georg Barkhausen in 1921.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] He also showed that all linear oscillators must have negative resistance.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] The first analysis of a nonlinear electronic oscillator model, the Van der Pol oscillator, was done by Balthasar van der Pol in 1927.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] He originated the term "relaxation oscillation" and was first to distinguish between linear and relaxation oscillators.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] He showed that the stability of the oscillations (limit cycles) in actual oscillators was due to the nonlinearity of the amplifying device.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] Further advances in mathematical analysis of oscillation were made by Hendrik Wade Bode and Harry Nyquist in the 1930s.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/electronic-oscillator] In 1969 Kaneyuki Kurokawa derived necessary and sufficient conditions for oscillation in negative-resistance circuits, which form the basis of modern microwave oscillator design.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/frequency-drift] In electrical engineering, and particularly in telecommunications, **frequency drift** is an unintended and generally arbitrary offset of an oscillator from its nominal frequency.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/frequency-drift] Causes may include component aging, changes in temperature that alter the piezoelectric effect in a crystal oscillator, or problems with a voltage regulator which controls the bias voltage to the oscillator.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/frequency-drift] Frequency drift is traditionally measured in Hz/s.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/frequency-drift] **Frequency stability** can be regarded as the absence (or a very low level) of frequency drift.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/frequency-drift] On a radio transmitter, frequency drift can cause a radio station to drift into an adjacent channel, causing illegal interference.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/frequency-drift] Because of this, Frequency allocation regulations specify the allowed tolerance for such oscillators in a type-accepted device.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/frequency-drift] A temperature-compensated, voltage-controlled crystal oscillator (TCVCXO) is normally used for frequency modulation.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/frequency-drift] On the receiver side, frequency drift was mainly a problem in early tuners, particularly for analog dial tuning, and especially on FM, which exhibits a capture effect.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/frequency-drift] However, the use of a phase-locked loop (PLL) essentially eliminates the drift issue.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/frequency-drift] For transmitters, a numerically controlled oscillator (NCO) also does not have problems with drift.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/frequency-drift] Drift differs from Doppler shift, which is a *perceived* difference in frequency due to motion of the source or receiver, even though the source is still producing the same wavelength.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/frequency-drift] It also differs from frequency deviation, which is the inherent and necessary result of modulation in both FM and phase modulation.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/pierce-oscillator] The **Pierce oscillator** is a type of electronic oscillator particularly well-suited for use in piezoelectric crystal oscillator circuits.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/pierce-oscillator] Pierce (1872–1956), the Pierce oscillator is a derivative of the Colpitts oscillator.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/pierce-oscillator] Virtually all digital IC clock oscillators are of Pierce type, as the circuit can be implemented using a minimum of components: a single digital inverter, one resistor, two capacitors, and the quartz crystal, which acts as a highly selective filter element.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/pierce-oscillator] The low manufacturing cost of this circuit and the frequency stability of quartz crystals make it advantageous for many consumer electronics applications.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/pierce-oscillator] If the circuit consists of perfect lossless components, the signal on C1 and C2 will be proportional to the impedance of each, and the ratio of the signal voltages at C1 and C2 will be C2/C1.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/pierce-oscillator] Normal crystals are lossless enough to make this a reasonable approximation: the amplifier does not drive the resonant circuit, but merely stays in sync with it, providing enough power to match losses.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/pierce-oscillator] A series resistor is occasionally shown in the amplifier output.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/pierce-oscillator] When used, a series resistor reduces loop gain, and amplifier gain must be increased to restore total loop gain to unity.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/pierce-oscillator] The purpose of using such a resistor in the amplifier circuit is to increase phase shift at startup, or when the crystal circuit is pulled out of phase by loading, and to eliminate the effects of amplifier non-linearity and of crystal overtones or spurious modes.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/pierce-oscillator] It is not part of the basic operation of the Pierce topology.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/pierce-oscillator] Extremely low-cost applications sometimes use a piezoelectric PZT crystal ceramic resonator rather than a piezoelectric quartz crystal resonator.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/pierce-oscillator] The crystal in combination with *C*1 and *C*2 forms a pi network band-pass filter, which provides a 180° phase shift and a voltage gain from the output to input at approximately the resonant frequency of the crystal.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/pierce-oscillator] To understand the operation, note that at the frequency of oscillation, the crystal appears inductive.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/pierce-oscillator] Thus, the crystal can be considered a large, high-*Q* inductor.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/pierce-oscillator] The combination of the 180° phase shift (i.e. inverting gain) from the pi network, and the negative gain from the inverter, results in a positive loop gain (positive feedback), making the bias point set by *R*1 unstable and leading to oscillation.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/pierce-oscillator] Recently, MEMS (Micro-Electro-Mechanical-System) resonators fabricated by surface micromachining have enabled ultra-low power stable pierce oscillators.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/pierce-oscillator] The tiny form factor of MEMS resonators greatly reduced the power consumption of the oscillator while keeping the good stability thanks to their very-high Q.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/pierce-oscillator] In addition to the biasing resistor *R*1, Ruan Lourens strongly recommends a series resistor *R*s between the output of the inverter and the crystal.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/pierce-oscillator] The series resistor *R*s reduces the chance of overtone oscillation and can improve start-up time.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/pierce-oscillator] This second resistor *R*s isolates the inverter from the crystal network.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/pierce-oscillator] This would also add additional phase shift to *C*1.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/pierce-oscillator] Pierce oscillators above 4 MHz should use a small capacitor rather than a resistor for *R*s.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/pierce-oscillator] This biasing resistor is commonly implemented by a MOSFET biased in its linear region to minimize parasitics.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/pierce-oscillator] The total capacitance seen from the crystal looking into the rest of the circuit is called the "load capacitance".
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/pierce-oscillator] When a manufacturer makes a "parallel" crystal, a technician uses a Pierce oscillator with a particular fixed load capacitance (often 18 or 20 pF) while trimming the crystal to oscillate at exactly the frequency written on its package.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/pierce-oscillator] To assure operation at the correct frequency, one must make sure the capacitances in the circuit match this value specified on the crystal's data sheet.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/pierce-oscillator] When a manufacturer makes a "series" crystal, a technician uses a different tuning procedure.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/pierce-oscillator] When a "series" crystal is used in a Pierce oscillator, the Pierce oscillator (as always) drives the crystal at nearly its parallel resonance frequency.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/pierce-oscillator] But that frequency is a few kilohertz higher than the series resonant frequency printed on the package of a "series" crystal.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/pierce-oscillator] Increasing the "load capacitance" slightly decreases the frequency generated by a Pierce oscillator, but never enough to reduce it all the way down to the series resonant frequency.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] As the advent of solid-state digital electronics in the 1980s allowed them to be made more compact and inexpensive, quartz timekeepers became the world's most widely used timekeeping technology, used in most clocks and watches as well as computers and other appliances that keep time.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] Chemically, quartz is a specific form of a compound called silicon dioxide.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] Many materials can be formed into plates that will resonate.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] However, quartz is also a piezoelectric material: that is, when a quartz crystal is subject to mechanical stress, such as bending, it accumulates electrical charge across some planes.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] In a reverse effect, if charges are placed across the crystal plane, quartz crystals will bend.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] Since quartz can be directly driven (to flex) by an electric signal, no additional transducer is required to use it in a resonator.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] Similar crystals are used in low-end phonograph cartridges: The movement of the stylus (needle) flexes a quartz crystal, which produces a small voltage, which is amplified and played through speakers.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] Quartz microphones are still available, though not common.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] Quartz has a further advantage in that its size does not change much as temperature fluctuates.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] Fused quartz is often used for laboratory equipment that must not change shape along with the temperature.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] A quartz plate's resonance frequency, based on its size, will not significantly rise or fall.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] Similarly, since its resonator does not change shape, a quartz clock will remain relatively accurate as the temperature changes.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] In the early 20th century, radio engineers sought a precise, stable source of radio frequencies and started at first with steel resonators.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] However, when Walter Guyton Cady found in the early 1920s that quartz can resonate with less equipment and better temperature stability, steel resonators disappeared within a few years.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] Later, scientists at National Institute of Standards and Technology (then the U.S.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] National Bureau of Standards) discovered that a crystal oscillator could be more accurate than a pendulum clock.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] The electronic circuit is an oscillator, an amplifier whose output passes through the quartz resonator.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] The resonator acts as an electronic filter, eliminating all but the single frequency of interest.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] The output of the resonator feeds back to the input of the amplifier, and the resonator assures that the oscillator runs at the exact frequency of interest.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] When the circuit is powered up, a single burst of shot noise (always present in electronic circuits) can cascade to bring the oscillator into oscillation at the desired frequency.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] If the amplifier were perfectly noise-free, the oscillator would not start.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] The frequency at which the crystal oscillates depends on its shape, size, and the crystal plane on which the quartz is cut.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] The positions at which electrodes are placed can slightly change the tuning as well.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] If the crystal is accurately shaped and positioned, it will oscillate at a desired frequency.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] In nearly all quartz clocks and watches, the frequency is 32768 Hz, and the crystal is cut in a small tuning fork shape on a particular crystal plane.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] This frequency is a power of two (32768 = 215), just high enough to exceed the human hearing range, yet low enough to keep electric energy consumption, cost and size at a modest level and to permit inexpensive counters to derive a 1-second pulse.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] The data line output from such a quartz resonator goes high and low 32768 times a second.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] This is fed into a flip-flop (which is essentially two transistors with a bit of cross-connection) which changes from low to high, or vice versa, whenever the line from the crystal goes from high to low.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] The output from that is fed into a second flip-flop, and so on through a chain of 15 flip-flops, each of which acts as an effective power of 2 frequency divider by dividing the frequency of the input signal by 2.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] The result is a 15-bit binary digital counter driven by the frequency that will overflow once per second, creating a digital pulse once per second.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] The pulse-per-second output can be used to drive many kinds of clocks.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] In analog quartz clocks and wristwatches, the electric pulse-per-second output is nearly always transferred to a Lavet-type stepping motor that converts the electronic input pulses from the flip-flops counting unit into mechanical output that can be used to move hands.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] Some analog quartz clocks feature a sweep second hand moved by a non-stepped battery or mains powered electric motor, often resulting in reduced mechanical output noise.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] In modern standard-quality quartz clocks, the quartz-crystal resonator or oscillator is cut in the shape of a small tuning fork (XY-cut), laser-trimmed or precision-lapped to vibrate at 32768 Hz.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] This frequency is equal to 215 cycles per second.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] A power of 2 is chosen so a simple chain of digital divide-by-2 stages can derive the 1 Hz signal needed to drive the watch's second hand.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] In most clocks, the resonator is in a small cylindrical or flat package, about 4 to 6 mm (0.16 to 0.24 in) long.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] The 32768 Hz resonator has become so common due to a compromise between the large physical size of low-frequency crystals for watches and the larger current drain of high-frequency crystals, which reduces the life of the watch battery.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] A cantilever made of quartz ( E = 1011 N/m2 = 100 GPa = 15 million psi; $\rho$ = 2.625 g/cm3 = 0.0948 lb/cu in), with a length of 3 mm (0.12 in) and a thickness of 0.3 mm (0.012 in), thus has a fundamental frequency around 33 kHz.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] The crystal is tuned to exactly 215 = 32768 Hz, or runs at a slightly higher frequency with inhibition compensation (see below).
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] The relative stability of the quartz resonator and its driving circuit is much better than its absolute accuracy.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] Though quartz has a very low coefficient of thermal expansion, temperature changes are the major cause of frequency variation in crystal oscillators.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] The most obvious way of reducing the effect of temperature on the oscillation rate is to keep the crystal at a constant temperature.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] For laboratory-grade oscillators, an oven-controlled crystal oscillator is used, in which the crystal is kept in a very small oven that is held at a constant temperature.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] This method is, however, impractical for consumer quartz clock and wristwatch movements.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] The crystal planes and tuning of consumer-grade clock crystal resonators used in wristwatches are designed for minimal temperature sensitivity to frequency and operate best at a temperature range of about 25 to 28 °C (77 to 82 °F).
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] The exact temperature where the crystal oscillates at its fastest is called the "turnover point" and can be chosen within limits.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] A well-chosen turnover point can minimize the negative effect of temperature-induced frequency drift, and hence improve the practical timekeeping accuracy of a consumer-grade crystal oscillator without adding significant cost.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] A higher or lower temperature will result in a −0.035 ppm/°C2 (slower) oscillation rate.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] So a ±1 °C temperature deviation will account for a (±1)2 × −0.035 ppm = −0.035 ppm rate change, which is equivalent to −1.1 seconds per year.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] If, instead, the crystal experiences a ±10 °C temperature deviation, then the rate change will be (±10)2 × −0.035 ppm = −3.5 ppm, which is equivalent to −110 seconds per year.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] Quartz watch manufacturers use a simplified version of the oven-controlled crystal oscillator method by recommending that their watches be worn regularly to ensure the best time-keeping performance.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] Regular wearing of a quartz watch significantly reduces the magnitude of environmental temperature swings, since a correctly designed watch case forms an expedient crystal oven that uses the stable temperature of the human body to keep the crystal oscillator in its most accurate temperature range.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] Some movement designs feature accuracy-enhancing features or self-rate and self-regulate.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] That is, rather than just counting vibrations, their computer program takes the simple count and scales it using a ratio calculated between an epoch set at the factory, and the most recent time the clock was set.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] Clocks that are sometimes regulated by service centers with the help of a precision timer and adjustment terminal after leaving the factory, also become more accurate as their quartz crystal ages and somewhat unpredictable aging effects are appropriately compensated.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] Autonomous high-accuracy quartz movements, even in wristwatches, can be accurate to within ±1 to ±25 seconds per year and can be certified and used as marine chronometers to determine longitude (the East–West position of a point on the Earth's surface) by means of celestial navigation.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] When time at the prime meridian (or another starting point) is accurately enough known, celestial navigation can determine longitude, and the more accurately time is known the more accurate the latitude determination.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] At latitude 45° one second of time is equivalent in longitude to 1,077.8 ft (328.51 m), or one-tenth of a second means 107.8 ft (32.86 m).
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] Regardless of the precision of the oscillator, a quartz analog or digital watch movement can have a trimmer condenser.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] They are generally found in older, vintage quartz watches – even many of the cheaper ones.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] A trimmer condenser or variable capacitor changes the frequency coming from the quartz crystal oscillator when its capacitance is changed.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] The frequency dividers remain unchanged, so the trimmer condenser can be used to adjust the electric pulse-per-second (or other desired time interval) output.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] The trimmer condenser looks like a small screw that has been wired into the circuit board.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] Typically, turning the screw clockwise speeds the movement up, and counterclockwise slows it down at about 1 second per day per 1⁄6 turn of the screw.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] Few newer quartz movement designs feature a mechanical trimmer condenser and rely on generally digital correction methods.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] It is possible for a computerized high-accuracy quartz movement to measure its temperature and adjust for that.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] For this the movement autonomously measures the crystal's temperature a few hundred to a few thousand times a day and compensates for this with a small calculated offset.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] Both analog and digital temperature compensation have been used in high-end quartz watches.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] In more expensive high-end quartz watches, thermal compensation can be implemented by varying the number of cycles to inhibit depending on the output from a temperature sensor.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] The COSC average daily rate standard for officially certified COSC quartz chronometers is ±25.55 seconds per year at 23 °C or 73 °F.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] To acquire the COSC chronometer label, a quartz instrument must benefit from thermo-compensation and rigorous encapsulation.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] Each quartz chronometer is tested for 13 days, in one position, at 3 different temperatures and 4 different relative humidity levels.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] Only approximately 0.2% of the Swiss made quartz watches are chronometer-certified by the COSC.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] These COSC chronometer-certified movements can be used as marine chronometers to determine longitude by means of celestial navigation.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] As of 2019, an autonomous light-powered high-accuracy quartz watch movement became commercially available which is claimed to be accurate to ± 1 second per year.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] Key elements to obtain the high claimed accuracy are applying an unusually shaped (for a watch) (AT-cut) quartz crystal operated at 223 or 8388608 Hz frequency, thermal compensation and hand selecting pre-aged crystals.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] AT-cut variations allow for greater temperature tolerances, specifically in the range of −40 to 125 °C (−40 to 257 °F), they exhibit reduced deviations caused by gravitational orientation changes.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] As a result, errors caused by spatial orientation and positioning become less of a concern.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] Many inexpensive quartz clocks and watches use a rating and compensation technique known as *inhibition compensation*.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] The crystal is deliberately made to run somewhat faster.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] After manufacturing, each module is calibrated against a precision clock at the factory and adjusted to keep accurate time by programming the digital logic to skip a small number of crystal cycles at regular intervals, such as 10 seconds or 1 minute.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] For a typical quartz movement, this allows programmed adjustments in 7.91 seconds per 30 days increments for 10-second intervals (on a 10-second measurement gate) or programmed adjustments in 1.32 seconds per 30 days increments for 60-second intervals (on a 60-second measurement gate).
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] The advantage of this method is that using digital programming to store the number of pulses to suppress in a non-volatile memory register on the chip is less expensive than the older technique of trimming the quartz tuning-fork frequency.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] The inhibition-compensation logic of some quartz movements can be regulated by service centers with the help of a professional precision timer and adjustment terminal after leaving the factory, though many inexpensive quartz watch movements do not offer this functionality.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] This is more than adequate to perform longitude determination by celestial navigation.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] These quartz movements over time become less accurate when no external time signal has been successfully received and internally processed to set or synchronize their time automatically, and without such external compensation generally fall back on autonomous timekeeping.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] The United States National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) has published guidelines recommending that these movements keep the time between synchronizations to within ±0.5 seconds to keep time correct when rounded to the nearest second.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] Some of these movements can keep the time between synchronizations to within ±0.2 seconds by synchronizing more than once spread over a day.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] Clock quartz crystals are manufactured in an ultra-clean environment, then protected by an inert ultra-high vacuum in hermetically sealed containers.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] Despite these measures, the frequency of a quartz crystal can slowly change over time.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] The effect of aging is much smaller than the effect of frequency variation caused by temperature changes, however, and manufacturers can estimate its effects.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] Generally, the aging effect eventually decreases a given crystal's frequency but it can also increase a given crystal's frequency.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] Factors that can cause a small frequency drift over time are stress relief in the mounting structure, loss of hermetic seal, contamination of the crystal lattice, moisture absorption, changes in or on the quartz crystal, severe shock and vibrations effects, and exposure to very high temperatures.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] Crystal aging tends to be logarithmic, meaning the maximum rate of change of frequency occurs immediately after manufacture and decays thereafter.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] Most of the aging will occur within the first year of the crystal's service life.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] Crystals do eventually stop aging (asymptotically), but it can take many years.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] Movement manufacturers can pre-age crystals before assembling them into clock movements.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] To promote accelerated aging the crystals are exposed to high temperatures.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] If a crystal is pre-aged, the manufacturer can measure its aging rates (strictly, the coefficients in the aging formula) and have a microcontroller calculate out the corrections over time.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] The initial calibration of a movement will stay accurate longer if the crystals are pre-aged.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] The advantage would end after subsequent regulation which resets any cumulative aging error to zero.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] A reason more expensive movements tend to be more accurate is that the crystals are pre-aged longer and selected for better aging performance.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] Sometimes, pre-aged crystals are hand selected for movement performance.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] Quartz chronometers designed as time standards often include a crystal oven, to keep the crystal at a constant temperature.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] Some self-rate and include "crystal farms", so that the clock can take the average of a set of time measurements.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] The Lavet-type stepping motors used in analog quartz clock movements which themselves are driven by a magnetic field (generated by the coil) can be affected by external (nearby) magnetism sources, and this may impact the rotor sprocket output.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] As a result, the mechanical output of analog quartz clock movements may temporarily stop, advance or reverse and negatively impact correct timekeeping.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] As the strength of a magnetic field almost always decreases with distance, moving an analog quartz clock movement away from an interfering external magnetic source normally results in a resumption of correct mechanical output.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] Some quartz wristwatch testers feature a magnetic field function to test if the stepping motor can provide mechanical output and let the gear train and hands deliberately spin overly fast to clear minor fouling.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] In general, magnetism encountered in daily life has no effect on digital quartz clock movements since there are no stepping motors in these movements.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] Powerful magnetism sources like MRI magnets can damage quartz clock movements.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] The piezoelectric properties of quartz were discovered by Jacques Curie and Pierre Curie in 1880.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] The vacuum tube oscillator was invented in 1912.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] An electrical oscillator was first used to sustain the motion of a tuning fork by the British physicist William Eccles in 1919; his achievement removed much of the damping associated with mechanical devices and maximised the stability of the vibration's frequency.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] The first quartz crystal oscillator was built by Walter G.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] Dye at the National Physical Laboratory in the UK and Warren Marrison at Bell Telephone Laboratories produced sequences of precision time signals with quartz oscillators.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] In October 1927 the first quartz clock was described and built by Joseph W.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] Marrison at Bell Telephone Laboratories.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] The 1927 clock used a block of crystal, stimulated by electricity, to produce pulses at a frequency of 50,000 cycles per second.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] A submultiple controlled frequency generator then divided this down to a usable, regular pulse that drove a synchronous motor.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] The next three decades saw the development of quartz clocks as precision time standards in laboratory settings; the bulky delicate counting electronics, built with vacuum tubes, limited their use elsewhere.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] In 1932 a quartz clock was able to measure tiny variations in the rotation rate of the Earth over periods as short as a few weeks.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] In Japan in 1932, Issac Koga developed a crystal cut that gave an oscillation frequency with greatly reduced temperature dependence.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] The National Bureau of Standards (now NIST) based the time standard of the US on quartz clocks between the 1930s and the 1960s, after which it transitioned to atomic clocks, which rely on the same mechanism that the International System of Units (SI) uses to define the second.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] In 1953, Longines deployed the first quartz movement.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] The wider use of quartz clock technology had to await the development of cheap semiconductor digital logic in the 1960s.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] The revised 1929 14th edition of *Encyclopædia Britannica* stated that quartz clocks would probably never be affordable enough to be used domestically.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] Their inherent physical and chemical stability and accuracy have resulted in the subsequent proliferation, and since the 1940s they have formed the basis for precision measurements of time and frequency worldwide.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] Developing quartz clocks for the consumer market took place during the 1960s.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] One of the first successes was a portable quartz clock called the *Seiko Crystal Chronometer QC-951*.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] This portable clock was used as a backup timer for marathon events in the 1964 Summer Olympics in Tokyo.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] In 1966, prototypes of the world's first quartz pocket watch were unveiled by Seiko and Longines in the Neuchâtel Observatory's 1966 competition.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] In 1967, both the CEH and Seiko presented prototypes of quartz wristwatches to the Neuchâtel Observatory competition.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] The world's first prototype analog quartz wristwatches were revealed in 1967: the Beta 1 revealed by the Centre Electronique Horloger (CEH) in Neuchâtel Switzerland, and the prototype of the Astron revealed by Seiko in Japan (Seiko had been working on quartz clocks since 1958).
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] The first Swiss quartz watch – the Ebauches SA Beta 21 – arrived at the 1970 Basel Fair.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] In December 1969, Seiko produced the world's first commercial quartz wristwatch, the Seiko Quartz-Astron 35SQ which is now honored with IEEE Milestone.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] The Astron had a quartz oscillator with a frequency of 8,192 Hz and was accurate to 0.2 seconds per day, 5 seconds per month, or 1 minute per year.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] The Astron was released less than a year prior to the introduction of the Swiss Beta 21, which was developed by 16 Swiss Watch manufacturers and used by Rolex, Patek and Omega in their electroquartz models.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] These first quartz watches were quite expensive and marketed as luxury watches.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] The inherent accuracy and eventually achieved low cost of production have resulted in the proliferation of quartz clocks and watches since that time.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] The introduction during the 1970s of metal–oxide–semiconductor (MOS) integrated circuits allowed a 12-month battery life from a single coin cell when driving either a mechanical Lavet-type stepping motor, a smooth sweeping non-stepping motor, or a liquid-crystal display (in an LCD digital watch).
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] Light-emitting diode (LED) displays for watches have become rare due to their comparatively high battery consumption.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] These innovations made the technology suitable for mass market adoption.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] In laboratory settings atomic clocks had replaced quartz clocks as the basis for precision measurements of time and frequency, resulting in International Atomic Time.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] By the 1980s, quartz technology had taken over applications such as kitchen timers, alarm clocks, bank vault time locks, and time fuzes on munitions, from earlier mechanical balance wheel movements, an upheaval known in watchmaking as the quartz crisis.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] Quartz timepieces have dominated the wristwatch and domestic clock market since the 1980s.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] Standard 'Watch' or Real-time clock (RTC) crystal units have become cheap mass-produced items on the electronic parts market.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] Since the 1980s, radio clocks are available, which use radio signals for their synchronization.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] Such clocks change automatically from standard time to daylight saving time.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] As these radio signals are transmitted in most cases in the longwave range, such devices can also work at places where radio reception conditions are poor.
[src:crystal-oscillators-deep/quartz-clock] With the proliferation of the Internet, consumer timekeeping devices (e.g. smartphones and smartwatches) may now automatically synchronize their internal clocks via automated protocols (e.g. network time protocol) to atomic clock time servers.
